  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. Global Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- International standards that guide national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering cases\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mechanisms\n\n4. Jurisdictional Coordination\n- Tracking cross-border financial transactions\n- Identifying and blocking international money laundering networks\n- Harmonizing legal definitions and enforcement approaches\n\n5. Regulatory Oversight\n- International banks and financial institutions subject to multiple jurisdictions\n- Consistent reporting and compliance standards\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Financial intelligence units (FIUs)\n- International databases and communication networks\n- Real-time monitoring of suspicious financial activities\n\nThese intersections help create a more comprehensive and coordinated approach to combating money laundering globally.",
